  "prompt": "Can a Greek question mark (;) be used instead of a semicolon (;) in a programming language such as C#, Java or Pascal?",
  "response": "No, the Greek question mark (;) cannot be used as a semicolon (;) in most programming languages, including C#, Java, or Pascal. \n\nThe semicolon (;) in these languages has a specific syntactic purpose for statement termination or separation, and the Greek question mark, while visually similar, is a different Unicode character. Using the Greek question mark would typically result in a syntax error.\n\nFor example, in C#:\n```csharp\n// This is correct\nint x = 5;\n\n// This would cause a syntax error\nint y = 6\uff1b  // Greek question mark\n```\n\nIf you accidentally use the Greek question mark, most IDEs and compilers will flag it as an error or unexpected token.\n\nAlways use the standard semicolon (;) when writing code in these programming languages.",
